magoers, Cinemagoing in wartime Britain, 1939-45 is the first book to offer an in-depth exploration of the impact that phenomena such as the black out, the blitz, food rationing, evacuation and conscription had on both the exhibition industry and the experiences of the picturegoers themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectsxGreat BritainxGreat BritainxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aAudiences.  aBlackout.  aBlitz.  aCinemagoing.  aEscapism.  aExhibition industry.  aExperientialism.  aShowmanship.  aStaffing.  aWar.1 aFarmer, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499736640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997366423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997366/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles